  "prompt": "Can a govt employee in india do a part time work?",
  "response": "In India, the rules regarding government employees engaging in part-time work are generally restrictive and are governed by the **Conduct Rules** applicable to government servants. Here are the key points to consider:\n\n1. **Prohibition on Unauthorized Employment**:  \n   - As per the **Central Civil Services (Conduct) Rules, 1964**, government employees are generally prohibited from engaging in any other employment or business without prior permission from the government.  \n   - Similar rules apply to state government employees under their respective conduct rules.\n\n2. **Exceptions and Permissions**:  \n   - In certain cases, government employees may be allowed to take up part-time work or teaching assignments **with prior approval**.  \n   - For example, teaching in universities or institutions (in areas relevant to their expertise) may be permitted if it does not interfere with their official duties.\n\n3. **Conflict of Interest**:  \n   - Any part-time work must not create a conflict of interest with the employee's official duties.  \n   - The government may deny permission if the part-time work could adversely affect the employee's performance or the integrity of their role.\n\n4. **Penalties for Violations**:  \n   - Engaging in part-time work without permission can lead to disciplinary action, including warnings, suspensions, or even dismissal.\n\n5. **Informal or Freelance Work**:  \n   - Informal or freelance work (e.g., consulting, writing, or online work) is also subject to these rules. Employees must disclose such activities and seek approval if required.\n\n### Conclusion:\nGovernment employees in India **cannot** take up part-time work without prior permission from their respective departments. It is advisable to consult the relevant Conduct Rules and seek formal approval before engaging in any additional employment. Violating these rules can lead to disciplinary action.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
